1. Make a stacked histogram plot for the feature variable: mass

In [3]:
def compare(ax, signal, bkgd, param, sigmas = 4, num_bins = 200,fontsize = 20):
    left1 = np.min([np.min(bkgd),np.min(signal)])
    left2 = np.min([np.mean(bkgd)-sigmas*np.std(bkgd), np.mean(signal)-sigmas*np.std(signal)])
    left = np.max([left1,left2])
    right1 = np.max([np.max(bkgd),np.max(signal)])
    right2 = np.max([np.mean(bkgd)+sigmas*np.std(bkgd), np.mean(signal)+sigmas*np.std(signal)])
    bins = np.linspace(np.max([left1,left2]),np.min([right1,right2]),num_bins)
    ax.hist([signal,bkgd], bins=bins, alpha = 0.5, color= ['r','b'], stacked = True,\
            label = ['Signal','Background'], ls='dashed', weights = [[n_higgs/n_total]*len(signal),[n_qcd/n_total]*len(bkgd)])
    #ax.hist(signal, bins=bins, alpha = 0.5,color= 'r',label = 'Signal', weights = [n_higgs/n_total]*len(signal))
    ax.legend(prop={'size': fontsize})
    ax.set_ylabel("Counts",fontsize=fontsize)
    ax.set_xlabel(param,fontsize=fontsize)
    ax.set_title('Stacked histograms of %s' % param,fontsize=int(fontsize*1.25))

  • Evaluate expected significance without any event selection.

    • Use Poisson statistics for significance calculation:
    • Compare your number of N_Higgs/(N_QCD) . If they are equivalent, explain your findings.

The expected yields of the background and the signal are 2000 and 50, respectively. We are assuming the background follows a Poission distribution with a mean of 2000. So the significance is probability of observing a background yield equal to or larger than 2000 + 50 = 2050:

In [5]:
prob = 1 - stats.poisson.cdf(2050,2000)
sigmas = stats.norm.ppf(1-prob)
print('The expected significance is %.5f-sigmas.' % sigmas)

The expected significance is 1.12822-sigmas.
In [6]:
result = n_higgs/np.sqrt(n_qcd)
print('My number of N_Higgs/(N_QCD) is %.5f.' % result)

My number of N_Higgs/(N_QCD) is 1.11803.

This N_Higgs/(N_QCD) value is close to the significance value of 1.12822 I found above.

The value of 1.11803 is the significance we would get if the background is exactly a Gaussian distribution with mean = 2000 and variance = 2000. And 1.12822 is what we get from our actual background, which is a Poisson distribution with mean = 2000 and variance = 2000.

A Poisson distribution with a large mean value would resemble a Gaussian distribution. And our mean of 2000 is relatively large. Thus the two values are approximately equivalent.

1. Identify mass cuts to optimize the expected significance.

  • Try different mass cuts systematically
    • Evaluate expeced significance for each set of mass cuts
    • Identify the set of the mass cuts which give you the highest significance.

Based on the observation that almost all of the variables' histograms are single-peaked, I think it's natural to assume that the optimal set of cuts on each of the variables would contain two cuts x1 and x2, where x1 < x2, and we would discard the data with its corresponding variable smaller than x1 or larger than x2.

Based on this assumption, I wrote a few Python functions below to facilitate the process of finding cuts.

In [7]:
# Returns the emperical CDF at points x given data.
# Function assumes x is a sorted array
def ecdf(data, x):
    data_size = len(data)
    data1 = sorted(data)
    result = np.zeros(len(x))
    j = 0
    for i in range(0,len(x)):
        while (j < data_size) and (data1[j] <= x[i]):
            j = j + 1
        result[i] = j
    result = result / data_size
    return result

# Returns four 2D arrays: X1,X2,s_diff,b_diff
# [X1,X2] is the meshgrid formed by the linear spaces x1 and x2=x1
# s_diff and b_diff are the ratio of the data and background with values between x1 and x2
# x1 should be a sorted array
def cut(signal,bkgd,x1):
    s = ecdf(signal,x1) # s is the emperical CDF of signal as a function of x1
    b = ecdf(bkgd,x1) # b is the emperical CDF of background as a function of x1
    X1,X2 = np.meshgrid(x1,x1)
    s_x1,s_x2 = np.meshgrid(s,s)
    b_x1,b_x2 = np.meshgrid(b,b)
    s_diff = s_x2 - s_x1
    b_diff = b_x2 - b_x1
    b_diff[b_diff==0] = 1e-12 # so that we don't divide by zero
    s_diff[X1>=X2] = 0 # ignore values with their x1>=x2
    b_diff[X1>=X2] = 1e-12 # ignore values with their x1>=x2
    significance = (s_diff*len(signal)/n_total*n_higgs)/np.sqrt(b_diff*len(bkgd)/n_total*n_qcd)
    return X1,X2,s_diff,b_diff,significance

# Determines x1 automatically
# bin_per_sd: bins per standard deviation of signal
def cut2(signal,bkgd,bins_per_sd):
    mean = np.mean(signal)
    sd = np.std(signal)
    step_size = sd/bins_per_sd
    x1 = np.arange(mean-5*sd,mean+5*sd+step_size,step_size)
    return cut(signal,bkgd,x1)
    

# Plots on ax the significance of signal and the ratio of signal left (s_diff)
# when we cut out sigal and background smaller than X1 and larger than X2
def plot_cuts(ax,X1,X2,significance,s_diff):
    #print(s_diff)
    left = X1[0,0]
    right = X1[0,len(X1)-1]
    im = ax.imshow(s_diff, origin='lower', extent=(left,right,left,right), cmap=cm.gnuplot2)
    CS = ax.contour(X1, X2, significance, linewidths=3,cmap=cm.Reds)
    ax.clabel(CS, inline=1, fontsize=10)
    CB = fig.colorbar(CS, shrink=0.8, extend='both')
    CBI = fig.colorbar(im, orientation='horizontal', shrink=0.8)
    l, b, w, h = ax.get_position().bounds
    CB.ax.set_position([l+w*1.2, b, w, h])
    CBI.ax.set_position([l, b-h*1.1, w, h])
    CB.set_label('Significance = N_Higgs/(N_QCD)', fontsize = 15)
    CBI.set_label('Ratio of signal remaining', fontsize=15)
    
    plt.grid(b=True, which='major', color='#009900', linestyle='-',linewidth=1)
    plt.minorticks_on()
    plt.grid(b=True, which='minor', color='#009900', linestyle='-', alpha=0.3)
    ax.set_xlabel('x1, left cut location', fontsize=15)
    ax.set_ylabel('x2, right cut location', fontsize=15)

# For each minimum Ratio of signal remaining allowed in the array p_span,
# returns the location and significance of the cut with the hightest significance.
# p_span should be sorted
def best_cuts(p_span,X1,X2,significance,signal_remaining):
    size = len(X1)**2
    x1 = X1.reshape(1,size)[0]
    x2 = X2.reshape(1,size)[0]
    s = significance.reshape(1,size)[0]
    p = signal_remaining.reshape(1,size)[0]
    p1 = p[p!=0]
    permutation = sorted(range(len(p1)), key=p1.__getitem__)
    x1 = x1[p!=0][permutation]
    x2 = x2[p!=0][permutation]
    s = s[p!=0][permutation]
    p = p1[permutation]
    x1_result = np.zeros(len(p_span))
    x2_result = np.zeros(len(p_span))
    s_result = np.zeros(len(p_span))
    j = len(p) - 1
    result = j
    for i in range(len(p_span)-1,-1,-1):
        while (j >= 0) and (p[j] >= p_span[i]):
            if s[j] > s[result]:
                result = j
            j = j - 1
        x1_result[i] = x1[result]
        x2_result[i] = x2[result]
        s_result[i] = s[result]
    return x1_result, x2_result, s_result

I plotted the significance of observation and the ratio of data left when we select the data with its mass within the range of (x1, x2) as a function of x1, the location of the cut on the left, and x2, the location of the cut on the right.

The optimal set of cuts should give as high an expected significance as possible, while at the same time doesn't cause a loss of too many signals. From the graph above, we can see that the 4.2-sigmas significance countour is although small but possible to let us to keep most of our signals after the cuts. So our best set of mass cuts should lie somewhere within this countour.

To find out exactly where the best set of cuts is at, I plotted below the the maximum significance achievable as a function of the minimum ratio of signal remaining allowed.

We can see the highest possible significance is about 4.6-sigmas, and we can keep at most about 60% of our data to achieve this significance. 60 percent is not very low, so we may say this 4.6-sigmas set of cuts is the best.
